----------------------------------------------------------------------
-- Whole-model verification summary
----------------------------------------------------------------------

-- Summary 1: Model captures dequeue operation with pre/post states, permissions, actors, resources, interfaces.
-- Summary 2: All acceptance criteria are modeled via reachability predicates for Post1 (patient presented) and Post2 (patient removed).
-- Summary 3: Edge cases (empty queue, priority ties, network failure, concurrency) are checked with dedicated assertions.
-- Summary 4: Conflicting NFR facts (performance <=2 channels vs availability >=2 channels) are retained as modeling assumptions.
-- Assumption 1: Pre1 represents a non-empty patient queue; edge case assertions override this for empty-queue scenarios.
-- Assumption 2: Priority ties are minimally modeled with a sig; deterministic selection is not enforced.
-- Assumption 3: Network failure is modeled as a channel not being authenticated.
-- Assumption 4: Concurrency is approximated via shared target resource and pre-state forbidding both operations reaching Post2.
-- Assumption 5: NFR facts use proxy constraints (channel count) and may conflict (performance vs availability).
-- Open issue 1: NetworkFailure and PriorityTie sigs have no connection to other model elements; assertions may be vacuously satisfiable.
-- Open issue 2: Conflicting NFR facts (nfr_fact_performance #channel <=2 vs nfr_fact_availability #channel >=2) cannot both hold for any instance; consider relaxing or scoping.
-- Open issue 3: Some edge case assertions (ec_safe_1) may be trivially true due to lack of empty-queue modeling.
-- Open issue 4: Test case predicates use singleton constraints (#REQ_PAT_DEQ_01 = 1) that limit scope unnecessarily.


